In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims April as National Child Abuse Prevention Month. He emphasizes the importance of caring for children and preventing child abuse and neglect. He highlights the need for a strong family unit and community involvement in protecting children. The Obama Administration has reinforced initiatives to prevent and treat child abuse, including signing the CAPTA Reauthorization Act of 2010. The Act provides new tools for identifying and addressing abuse and neglect, and also focuses on addressing risk factors such as substance abuse, mental illness, and domestic violence. The administration is also supporting programs that improve coordination of early childhood services. President Obama calls on all Americans to observe this month by participating in programs and activities that prevent child abuse and meet children's needs.